@flexiarg collaboration-coherence/magical-thinking
@title Expect Process Cost; Name the Friction
@keywords magical-thinking, friction-budget, process-cost, ideal-platform, premature-tooling
@audience peer-learning facilitators, project conveners, tool-builders
@tone practical
@style pattern
@references [peeragogy/use-or-make collaboration-coherence/stasis collaboration-coherence/navel-gazing]

! conclusion: Problem-solving in collaborative work always takes time, attention, and friction; expecting tools, platforms, or processes to come pre-built (or to "just work" once installed) is the failure mode that strips a project of its own learning.  The pattern is to name the magical assumption explicitly, estimate its friction cost, and budget for the work the project will actually have to do — preserving the friction-as-learning property the project depends on.
  + context: Voluntary peer-learning projects routinely reach for the next tool / framework / process under the implicit hope that adoption will dissolve the underlying problem.  Sometimes adoption helps; often it just relocates the problem (now we have the same coordination issue, plus a new tool to learn).  The deeper failure is that "magical thinking" robs the project of the *process* — the working-through that constitutes much of what a peer-learning project is meant to produce.  If the tooling were truly that good, the handbook wouldn't need to exist.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: faith in tooling ↔ attention to process cost.
    Real: tooling really does matter — a good substrate halves the work.  But the marginal value of tooling is bounded above by the project's actual problem; past that bound, tooling investment is displacement.  Both effects are continuous; the question is whether the project knows which side of the bound it is on.
    Irreducible: a project cannot simultaneously be working on the underlying problem and waiting for tooling to make the underlying problem disappear.  At any moment one or the other is happening.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever the project hits a frustration that has a "if only we had X" response, whenever a new tool appears in the discourse, and whenever a contributor proposes adoption rather than configuration of an existing tool.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Name the magical assumption: when the next tool / process / framework is proposed, write down what specifically is expected to become easier, by how much, and on what timescale.  The act of writing usually changes the proposal.
    (2) Friction budget: maintain an explicit estimate of the project's available attention.  New adoptions get a friction line item — onboarding, configuration, ongoing maintenance, integration with existing tooling.  When the budget overruns, something gets dropped.
    (3) Adopt-after-use: try to solve the underlying problem with existing tooling first.  If the existing tooling visibly fails, the diagnostic information is what justifies adoption.  Without that diagnostic, adoption is speculation.
    (4) Preserve process learning: when a frustration is dissolved by tooling, ask what the project was *learning* from that frustration.  If the answer is something useful, recover it deliberately (e.g. document the now-tooling-handled problem so contributors who need to understand it still can).
    (5) Magical-thinking audit: periodically review which assumptions about tooling have actually paid off and which have not.  Pattern revision based on evidence beats the next adoption proposal.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: every tooling adoption decision has a recorded prior expectation and a recorded post-hoc audit.  Failing when: tools accumulate without commensurate progress on the underlying problem, or the project repeatedly proposes the same kind of tooling solution with no acknowledgement of why prior versions didn't deliver.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Pre-built fantasy: "the ideal platform would come with X already solved" — said without engagement with whether such a platform exists or could exist.
    - Adoption cascade: a new tool is adopted, brings a problem, which is solved by adopting another tool, and so on; each round defers rather than discharges the underlying issue.
    - Friction-blindness: contributors propose adoption without naming the onboarding or maintenance cost; the cost is paid silently by whoever ends up doing it.
    - Process-stripping: a frustration that was teaching the project something gets dissolved by tooling, and the project later realises the learning is gone with it.
    - Stress-driven habit shift: under pressure the project falls back on already-trained tools rather than reaching for the most appropriate one (echoing the Science Magazine quote in the source — habit displaces goal-directed choice under stress).
